Adam Stegerwald has been elected as the chairman of the <span style="color: #000000;">Center Party</span>. He seems to represent a rightward turn from Marx, despite his trade union background, and will preside over a <span style="color: #000000;">Center Party</span> less inclined to compromise with the left. He views the <span style="color: #000000;">Center Party</span> as a prototype for a Christian, democratic, German, and social party, and aims to transform it according to the principles laid out in his proposed "Essen program" eight years prior. 

The <span style="color: #000000;">Center Party</span>'s middle class wing are in uproar over the vote, despite Stegerwald conceding his leadership of the Reichstag delegation and the Minister-Presidency to his protege Heinrich Brüning. [? if dnvp_ideology == "Radical": His election also attracts some Protestant <span style="color: #3E88B3;">**DNVP**</span> dissidents and industrialists, who may result in a shift of the party towards the right. ?]